Autonomous agents introduce safety concerns that don't exist with simple text generation. An agent that can take actions can also take wrong actions—booking incorrect flights, deleting important data, accessing unauthorized information, or producing harmful content. Production agents need robust safety controls.

Bedrock Guardrails apply to agents just as they do to direct model calls. Configure a guardrail for your agent, and it filters both inputs and outputs. This catches prompt injection attempts, blocks harmful content generation, and enforces content policies. The guardrail acts as a safety layer around the entire agent interaction.

```python
agent_config = {
    'guardrailConfiguration': {
        'guardrailIdentifier': 'GUARDRAIL_ID',
        'guardrailVersion': '1'
    }
}
```

IAM policies control what actions agents can actually perform in AWS. Even if an agent tries to take an unauthorized action, IAM denies it. Scope agent roles to the minimum necessary permissions. An agent that queries product information should not have permission to modify inventory or delete records.

```json
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": ["dynamodb:GetItem", "dynamodb:Query"],
      "Resource": "arn:aws:dynamodb:*:*:table/products"
    },
    {
      "Effect": "Deny",
      "Action": ["dynamodb:DeleteItem", "dynamodb:UpdateItem"],
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}
```

Human-in-the-loop patterns require approval for sensitive operations. Lambda functions can return control to the application instead of executing actions, presenting proposed actions to humans for approval. This makes sense for high-stakes operations like refunds, data modifications, or external communications.

Timeouts and iteration limits prevent runaway agents. Configure session timeouts so abandoned conversations don't consume resources indefinitely. Set maximum iterations to prevent infinite loops where an agent keeps retrying the same failing approach. Step Functions workflows can add additional timeout controls around agent invocations.

Monitoring agent behavior provides visibility into what agents are doing. Log all actions with CloudWatch. Set up metrics for action invocation rates. Alert on unusual patterns that might indicate problems—an agent making hundreds of API calls per minute suggests something has gone wrong.

Testing agent behavior validates that safety controls work. Create golden datasets with test cases that should be refused—requests to delete all data, reveal PII, or take other harmful actions. Run these tests against agents to verify they respond appropriately.
